PSL190H1-S-20209.courseTitle: Biomedical Research at the Cutting Edge
PSL190H1-S-20209.courseDescription: Explore the thought processes, logic, motivation, techniques, analysis and impact of recent high-profile publications to gain insight into the enterprise of science. Outstanding scientists present recent high-impact papers, and students will examine the research in depth, focusing on the underlying questions, experimental approach, results and significance. Restricted to first-year students. Not available for CR/NCR option.
PSL190H1-S-20209.prerequisite: SBI4U and SCH4U (Grade 12 University Preparation Biology and Chemistry); permission of Department
PSL190H1-S-20209.webTimetableInstructions: This course has restricted enrollment for newly admitted first-year science degree students with fewer than 4 credits.
PSL190H1-S-20209.deliveryInstructions: Course Delivery: Lectures will be delivered online synchronous and assessments will take place during the regularly scheduled class times. Classes are mandatory and will involve group work. Students will need access to Quercus and the ability to use collaboration software such as Bb collaborate, Teams or Zoom.

PSL201Y1-Y-20209.courseDescription: A survey course covering all organ systems intended for students who are not proceeding further in Physiology.
PSL201Y1-Y-20209.exclusion: Any 300-level PSL course taken previously or concurrently
PSL201Y1-Y-20209.deliveryInstructions: Lectures will be delivered online; learning is self-paced and not reliant on a meeting schedule. Term tests will be timed and will take place Tuesdays from 18:00 to 20:00 (Toronto time) on scheduled dates (TBA). Lectures 2h/week and optional help sessions 1h/week. Students will need access to the internet and Quercus and the ability to use collaboration software such Bb collaborate.

PSL280H1-F-20209.courseTitle: Introduction to Physiologic Adaptations of Marine Mammals
PSL280H1-F-20209.courseDescription: Systems approach to physiology of marine mammals in their aquatic environment. Highlights unique features of cardiovascular, respiratory, renal, urinary, and reproductive systems. Introduces relevant physiology, and makes comparisons to human condition and disease.
PSL280H1-F-20209.prerequisite: (BIO120H1, BIO130H1), CHM136H1/CHM138H1/CHM151Y1 or permission of the course coordinator.
PSL280H1-F-20209.deliveryInstructions: Lectures will be delivered online per the meeting schedule. Term tests will be timed and will take place Thursdays 12:00 to 14:00 (Toronto time) on scheduled dates (TBA). Active learning sessions (PRA) may be offered in the regularly scheduled practical times as student and TA safety allows and will also be recorded for remote learners. Students will need access to the internet and Quercus and the ability to use collaboration software such as Bb collaborate. If students cannot attend the in-person active learning for the entire term, please contact the Course Coordinator (c.wittnich@utoronto.ca) as soon as possible with the Subject line: “PSL280H Remote”.

PSL304H1-F-20209.courseTitle: Topics in Cellular, Molecular and Organismic Physiology I
PSL304H1-F-20209.courseDescription: Control systems, feedback, networks, and both neonatal and adult cardiovascular and respiratory control are the topics examined in detail using homeostasis as a unifying theme. Tutorials involve computer simulations, case studies and/or experimental design. This course is designed for students in the Physiology Specialist and Biological Physics Specialist Programs, although permission is granted to students in other programs upon approval by the Department.

Check your course status in August. If you have been approved, a status of APP will appear; if you have been refused, a status of REF will appear. For additional information please contact Eva Eng at physiology.undergrad@utoronto.ca.
PSL304H1-F-20209.deliveryInstructions: Lectures will be delivered online per the meeting schedule. Additional contact with students will be made through scheduled online tutorials or help sessions. Students will need to be able to access the internet and Quercus and to use collaboration software such as Bb collaborate, Teams or Zoom.

PSL305H1-S-20209.courseTitle: Topics in Cellular, Molecular and Organismic Physiology II
PSL305H1-S-20209.courseDescription: Molecular, cellular and organismic physiology of the central nervous system, gut, pancreas and glucose-sensing tissues; CNS diseases, obesity and diabetes are used as model systems. Tutorials involve computer simulations. This course is designed for students in the Physiology Specialist and Biological Physics Specialist Programs, although permission is granted to students in other programs upon approval by the Department.
PSL305H1-S-20209.webTimetableInstructions: This course may be added during your enrolment start date using ROSI/ACORN, but will appear with an interim status (INT) until reviewed by department. PSL310H1-S-20209.courseDescription: Improved clinical reasoning will reduce the current likelihood that most people will suffer at least one medical diagnostic error, errors that contribute to ~10% of patient deaths. Learn to apply strategies of critical thinking and principles of physiology to solve clinical cases. Shadow a healthcare professional. Not eligible for CR/NCR option.
PSL310H1-S-20209.deliveryInstructions: Lectures will be delivered online per the meeting schedule. Term tests will be timed and will take place during class times (Toronto-EST) on scheduled dates (TBA). Additional contact with students will be made through scheduled online sessions. Students will need to be able to access the internet and Quercus and to use collaboration software such as Bb collaborate, Teams or Zoom.

PSL350H1-S-20209.courseDescription: Extend molecular biology concepts to current scientific literature in mammalian physiology. Apply these principles to disease and complex behaviours. Discuss bioethical issues raised by these techniques and their application. Benefit from three weeks in small group seminars lead by research professors focusing on current advances in mammalian molecular biology.
PSL350H1-S-20209.webTimetableInstructions:
Online Lectures: Tuesdays 10:00 to 12:00 p.m.

Online Practicals: Thursdays 15:00 to 16:00 OR 16:00 to 17:00
PSL350H1-S-20209.deliveryInstructions: Course Delivery: Lectures will be delivered online synchronous and assessments will take place during the regularly scheduled class times. Term tests will be timed and will take place during class times (Toronto-EST) on scheduled dates (TBA). Thursday practicals are mandatory and involve group work. Students will need access to Quercus and the ability to use collaboration software such as Bb collaborate, Teams or Zoom.

PSL374H1-S-20209.courseDescription: A problem-based laboratory course focused on the integration and control of organ systems to understand body functions. PSL404H1-F-20209.courseDescription: Regenerative medicine promises to restore body function that has been lost due to disease, damage or age. Students will explore selected molecular, stem cell and tissue engineering developments to better understand how the body normally functions and how cells, tissues, and organs can be repaired or replaced.
PSL404H1-F-20209.webTimetableInstructions: This course may be added during your enrollment start date using ROSI/ACORN, but will appear with an interim status (INT) until reviewed by department. Check your course status in August. If you have been approved, a status of APP will appear; if you have been refused, a status of REF will appear. PSL404H1-F-20209.deliveryInstructions: Course Delivery: Lectures will be delivered online (synchronous and/or asynchronous) and assessments will take place during the regularly scheduled class times. Thursday classes are mandatory and involve group work. Students will need access to Quercus and the ability to use collaboration software such as Bb collaborate, Teams or Zoom.

PSL420H1-F-20209.courseDescription: This course provides an in-depth review of the development and function of the male and female reproductive systems. Topics include sex determination and differentiation, steroidogenesis, gametogenesis, hormonal control of the reproductive axis, the female ovulatory cycle, fertilization and implantation, infertility and assisted reproduction approaches.

PSL421H1-S-20209.courseTitle: Pregnancy and Birth: From Implantation to Newborn Life
PSL421H1-S-20209.courseDescription: General overview of the integrated physiological events associated with fetal development, pregnancy and birth. The approach emphasizes physiological processes using insights gained from studies of humans, animals, cells and genes. Where appropriate the clinical consequences of aberrant development are reviewed.
PSL421H1-S-20209.deliveryInstructions: Course Delivery: Lectures will be delivered online synchronous and assessments will be timed and will take place during class times (Toronto - EST) on scheduled dates (TBA). Students will need access to Quercus and the ability to use collaboration software such as Bb collaborate, Teams or Zoom.

PSL424H1-S-20209.courseTitle: Cellular and Molecular Basis of Endocrine Disorders
PSL424H1-S-20209.courseDescription: Explore how researchers uncover the molecular and cellular basis of endocrine disorders. Learn about experimental design, state-of-the-art research tools, and data interpretation. Topics include disorders in: hormone regulation, secretion and action; circadian rhythms; and sexual development and reproduction. Each week students engage in class discussion related to research seminars delivered by faculty.
PSL424H1-S-20209.deliveryInstructions: Course Delivery: Lectures will be delivered online synchronous and assessments will take place during the regularly scheduled class times. Classes are mandatory and involve group work. Students will need access to Quercus and the ability to use collaboration software such as Bb collaborate, Teams or Zoom.

PSL425H1-F-20209.courseTitle: Integrative Metabolism and its Endocrine Regulation
PSL425H1-F-20209.courseDescription: This course integrates the newest findings and experimental approaches from cellular and molecular biology into metabolic function at the tissue, organ and whole body level.
PSL425H1-F-20209.deliveryInstructions: Course Delivery: Lectures will be available only as online synchronous and at their regularly scheduled times, and synchronous assessments will take place during the regularly scheduled class times. Students will need access to Quercus and the ability to use collaboration software such as Bb collaborate, Teams or Zoom.

PSL432H1-S-20209.courseDescription: Theoretical treatment of neurophysiology. Mathematical modeling and analysis of neurophysiological systems.

PSL440Y1-Y-20209.courseDescription: Introduction to systems neuroscience. A review of basic neuroanatomy and physiology followed by in-depth study of selected sensory and motor systems, with an emphasis on clinical applications in the second term. Students with an elementary neuroscience background progress to reading neuroscience literature on their own.
PSL440Y1-Y-20209.deliveryInstructions: Lectures will be posted online. Help sessions will be conducted during the regularly scheduled class time and efforts will be made to provide an online recording of the help sessions. Assessments will likely take place during regularly scheduled class time. Students need access to the internet and Quercus and the ability to use collaboration software such Bb collaborate.

PSL445H1-F-20209.courseDescription: Overview of the fundamentals of cellular and molecular aspects of brain function. Course material is updated yearly to reflect the rapid evolution of ideas in Neuroscience.

PSL446H1-S-20209.courseDescription: Explore topics in neurological disorders and treatments to reinforce and expand your knowledge of cellular and molecular neurophysiology. Course material is updated yearly to reflect the rapid evolution of ideas in this area.
PSL446H1-S-20209.prerequisite: PSL300H1, PSL301H1, CJH332H1 or permission of instructor

PSL450H1-F-20209.courseTitle: Mechanisms of Neural and Endocrinal Secretion
PSL450H1-F-20209.courseDescription: Exocytosis and other aspects of secretion mainly in neurons and neuroendocrine cells, but also in pancreatic cells. Topics include synapse anatomy and physiology, synaptic plasma membrane and vesicle proteins, membrane fusion, genetic tools, endocrine secretion, plasticity in neurotransmitter release, diseases arising from secretion defects.
PSL450H1-F-20209.deliveryInstructions: Lectures are live-streamed and recorded as per the meeting schedule (permitting synchronous delivery, but also asynchronous attendance). Students will need access to Quercus and the ability to use collaboration software such as Bb collaborate, Teams or Zoom.

PSL452H1-F-20209.courseDescription: Biophysics and molecular biology of ion channels. Topics include equivalent circuits for cells, molecular structure of voltage-gated channels, distribution of channels, relationship between single-channel and whole-cell recording, and regulation of channel function by voltage, phosphorylation, G-proteins and metabolites.

PSL462H1-S-20209.courseDescription: Heart anatomy and development, ion channels and contractile proteins involved in cardiac and smooth muscle contraction are studied. Emphasis is on regulation of electrical and contractile function of kinases, metabolism, volume and ions.
PSL462H1-S-20209.deliveryInstructions: Course Delivery: Lectures will be delivered online synchronous and assessments will take place during the regularly scheduled class times. PSL470H1-S-20209.courseDescription: Development of the cardiovascular system from conception to adulthood with particular emphasis on maturational changes, age-related differences and developmental problems from cellular/molecular to whole organ/system.
PSL470H1-S-20209.deliveryInstructions: Course Delivery: Lectures will be delivered online per the meeting schedule. Students will need access to Quercus and the ability to use collaboration software such as Bb collaborate, Teams or Zoom.

PSL472H1-S-20209.courseDescription: This course covers the physiology underlying sleep and circadian rhythms, and their impact on important physiological processes and health. The integrative nature of the basic physiological processes is emphasized via discussions and clinical presentations. Overall, the aim is to present the full spectrum of integrative physiology from molecules and cells to understanding the sick patient.
